  "slug": "snowball-cookies",
  "title": "Snowball cookies",
  "subtitle": "Mexican wedding cookies rolled in icing sugar",
  "excerpt": "Small, round, pecan-and-butter cookies rolled in icing sugar while warm, then rolled again when cool. They crumble at the bite and taste primarily of browned butter and toasted nut.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Mexican wedding cookies and Russian tea cakes are the same biscuit. The recipe appears under both names in mid-twentieth-century American domestic cookery. The technique (a short, nut-studded butter dough rolled in icing sugar) has cognates in many European traditions (Greek kourabiedes, Italian polverone). The double-rolling (warm then cool) is documented from the 1950s onwards.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "These are one of the most forgiving biscuits to make: no rolling, no cutters, no icing. Roll the dough into balls, bake, roll in icing sugar. The double-rolling matters: the first coat while the cookies are still warm sticks to the surface and forms a base layer; the second coat when they are cold is what gives them the thick, snowy finish.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Toast the pecans before chopping them. ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Toasting nuts",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpaehoex0000x4v47t2h5kml"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " takes 8 minutes in the oven and makes a noticeable difference to the final flavour.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
